<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-058-347 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 407 405</DOCID><JOURNAL>Government Computer News  Sept 16 1991 v10 n19 p1(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>AIX goes native on IBM ES/9000. (IBM's AIX/ESA for its ES/9000mainframe computers) (product announcement)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Taft, Darryl K.; Vizachero, Rick.andM;</AUTHOR><SUMMARY>IBM introduces the AIX/ESA operating system, the first version ofUNIX to run on its ES/9000 mainframe computers.andP;  AIX/ESA will bebased on the Open Software Foundation's OSF/1; OSF has said itintends to meet the Posix standard with OSF/1.andP;  Prior to AIX/ESA,versions of AIX for mainframes ran as guests under the VMoperating system; the most popular version of UNIX runningnatively on an IBM-type mainframe is offered by Amdahl Corp. IBMData Systems Div Pres Nick Donofrio says AIX/ESA shows thecompany's commitment to open-systems computing and to the OpenSoftware Foundation; earlier IBM announced that its MVS operatingsystem will comply with Posix in the future.andP;  Also introduced aremore than 100 new products and services, including fourwater-cooled and three air-cooled ES/9000 models; the new Model490 costs from $2.9 million, while the water-cooled,three-processor Model 740 costs $11.6 million.andM;</SUMMARY><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Product introduction).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Product:   AIX/ESA (Operating system) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionSoftware DesignMainframe computersOperating systemsUnix-like operating systemsPOSIX standardOpen Software Foundation.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>NEW YORK -- IBM Corp. last week announced it intends to deliver its firstUnix version to run as a native operating system on its mainframes.andM;AIX/ESA will run natively on IBM's ES/9000 computers.andP;  The company will basethe new operating system on the Open Software Foundation's OSF/1.andP;  The OpenSoftware Foundation has announced it intends to meet the Posix standard withOSF/1.andM;Earlier AIX versions for mainframes ran as guests under the VM operatingsystem.andP;  Amdahl Corp. has provided the most widely used native Unix forIBM-type mainframes.andM;AIX is one of the few variants of Unix that a company other than ATandamp;T Co. hasconstructed from the ground up.andP;  Some improvements in the code were added toimprove its performance on mainframes.andM;&quot;Our intent to provide AIX/ESA reflects our continuing commitment toopen-systems computing and the Open Software Foundation,&quot; said Nick Donofrio,president of IBM's Data Systems Division.andM;IBM also announced that its MVS operating system will become Posix-compliantin the future.andP;  &quot;IBM's direction is to implement the currently accepted Posixstandard in MVS,&quot; an IBM announcement said.andM;IBM also announced more than 100 new products and services, including sevennew ES/9000s.andP;  Four of the new computers are water-cooled and three areair-cooled.andP;  Some use up to three CPUs.andM;Prices range from $2.9 million for an ES/9000 Model 490 up to $11.6 millionfor a water-cooled three-processor system, the ES/9000 Model 740.andM;Security software to help protect against viruses, improve workstationsecurity and enhance cryptographic capabilities was among the new productsunveiled.andM;Database application development software, storage devices and networkproducts also arrived.andP;  Among the announcements was the &quot;InformationWarehouse,&quot; a framework for delivering access to data stored on multiple hossystems, whether from IBM or other vendors.andM;IBM also announced Image-Plus/2, a networked or standalone imaging systembased on the PS/2 and OS/2 Extended Edition.andP;  Developed in conjunction withEastman Kodak Co., it is Systems Application Architecture-compliant.andO;</TEXT></DOC>